================================================================================
SERVICENOW ACCESS CONTROL LIST (ACL) — CSA 2025 NOTES
================================================================================

1) WHAT IS ACL?
---------------
• ACL (Access Control List) is a security rule.
• It controls who can access data in ServiceNow.
• ACLs are the **highest level of data security** in ServiceNow.

ACLs control access at:
• Table level
• Record (row) level
• Field (column) level

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
2) LEVELS OF SECURITY IN SERVICENOW
-----------------------------------
1. Login Security
   • User must be authenticated.
   • Controlled by user account status and roles.

2. Application & Module Access
   • Controlled by roles.
   • Determines what applications/modules are visible.

3. Data Access (ACL)
   • Controls access to tables, records, and fields.
   • Even if a user sees a module, ACLs decide what data is accessible.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
3) ACL OPERATIONS (EXAM-CRITICAL)
---------------------------------
STANDARD DATABASE OPERATIONS (CRUD):
• Create
• Read
• Update
• Delete

SERVICENOW-SPECIFIC OPERATIONS:
• Execute (run scripts)
• Add CI Relationships
• Save as Template
• Report On
• Personalize Choice

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
4) TYPES OF ACL RULES (VERY IMPORTANT)
--------------------------------------

A) table.none
• Applies to the entire table.
• Controls access to records in the table.
• If denied → user cannot see records at all.

Example:
• incident.none (Read)

--------------------------------------

B) table.*
• Applies to **all fields** in the table.
• User can see records but field access is evaluated.

Example:
• incident.* (Read)

--------------------------------------

C) table.field
• Applies to a **specific field**.
• Used to hide or restrict individual fields.

Example:
• incident.caller_id (Read)

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
5) ACL EVALUATION LOGIC (HOW ACL WORKS)
---------------------------------------
When a user tries to access data:

1. ServiceNow checks if an ACL exists.
2. If NO ACL exists → access is GRANTED.
3. If ACL exists → ACL is evaluated.
4. If conditions pass → access is GRANTED.
5. If conditions fail → access is DENIED.

NOTE:
• ACLs also apply to reports and APIs.
• If data is restricted by ACL, it cannot be accessed via reporting.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
6) ACL CONDITIONS
-----------------
Access is granted if ALL conditions pass:

• Required Roles
• Conditions (filters)
• Script (if used)

If any condition fails → access denied.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
7) ADMIN OVERRIDE
------------------
• If enabled → Admin can bypass ACL.
• If disabled → ACL applies even to admin users.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
8) ROLES REQUIRED FOR ACL MANAGEMENT
------------------------------------
• admin
   - View ACLs
• security_admin
   - Create or modify ACLs
   - Requires role elevation (session-based)

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
9) DEFAULT ACL BEHAVIOR
-----------------------
• When a table is created with "Create Access Controls" enabled:
   - System auto-creates 4 ACLs:
     • Create
     • Read
     • Write
     • Delete

• If no ACL exists → data is accessible by default.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
10) KEY CSA EXAM TAKEAWAYS
--------------------------
• ACLs control data access, not UI visibility.
• ACLs are evaluated before showing data.
• No ACL = access allowed.
• table.none → record access.
• table.* → all fields.
• table.field → specific field.
• ACLs apply to forms, lists, reports, and APIs.
• security_admin role is required to modify ACLs.

================================================================================
END OF ACL — CSA 2025
================================================================================
